Knee Pain is present in many lives today

The worst part? A lot of those people think it’s impossible to fix, chronic or not. Or, they are just waiting for it to get better.

More likely than not though, you CAN do something about it💪🏼

These 2 movements are perfect to start your journey in reclaiming your knees. Plus, doing these back to back will take 15 minutes or less in total!

Backwards walking = bloodflow🦵🩸

Tibialis Raises = strengthening the shin🛡️ (you’ll also feel bloodflow in the shin like you’ve most likely never felt before)

Try these out for 3-4 days out of the week. Then build consistency from there based on how your body feels.

Get back to me on the results!📈
#ATG @athletictruthgroup @atgforcoaches

@kneesovertoesguy changed the game by popularizing this one...

Debatably the most valuable lower body exercise of all time🤔

Ever since I started ATG training, this has been a staple in my routine.

It was one of those exercises that I thought looked a little peculiar, and because of that, I couldn’t wait to give it a shot!

Working to not only gain comfortability in this position at first, but also gaining strength in it through loading has given me lower body ability that will undoubtedly serve me for the rest of my life, as long as I continue to maintain it and work on it💪🏼

In an ATG Split Squat, you’re improving: 

✅Balance between both sides

✅Knee over toe ability

✅Strength in the lower body

✅Lengthening of the hip flexors

5 sets of 5 repetitions on each leg 3 times a week

*if you can already do it loaded on flat ground, start at 1x a week

ALSO, bringing up the front heel like I do in this video to achieve full hamstring - calf coverage is completely fine!

Give it a shot! 

Kendama players…what do you think? Do you think being able to own different ranges of motion will supplement your kendama play and even enhance it??🤷🏻‍♂️

You’ll only know if you try!👊🏼

A co-worker of mine asked me if I had anything I do for wrists and I thought I would just make a video to post about it📱

Some of you may have wrists ranked last on your list of things to put in work for because you've never experienced pain there. I totally get it, it wasn't until I started working at an ice cream shop and experienced pain and soreness myself that I started to give my wrists any attention. But once you experience it, it's really aggravating. 

Whenever I have wrist pain, I get so annoyed because then I realize how much I’m using my wrist in everyday life, as well as playing kendama of course. It’s kinda like “am I actually experiencing pain in my wrist right now?” because I think “how did that even happen?”🤦🏻‍♂️

But the truth is, it’s more inclined to happen the longer we go without working on it

Hope this video helps someone! And maybe even some of my coworkers who may see this🍦

Kendama players, have you ever thought about it this way? 

It dawned on me that every great player in history has been able to get into positions that other players cannot. 

Elite kendama skill is reached through hours and hours of practice, no one can argue that. It’s a never ending journey as no matter how skillful one gets…there will always be more tricks to learn and consistency to pursue.

BUT…it’s the physical capability that allows a player to play for those amount of hours in order to improve. Knee bends, squatting, bending of the back, quick feet movement, ankle strength and flexibility, shoulder ability…these are all just a couple of things that are happening when playing kendama. It is a low intensity, full body endeavor after all.

The last thing we want as kendama players is to have our playing time be limited to the pain we are experiencing while playing, instead of being limited by our INTEREST in playing and determination towards landing tricks.

Do you think it hurt to play kendama for all the top players to get to where they were/are? Doubt it. And if you’re a player reading this in some sort of pain thinking “well I’m still pretty good,” how good would you be if you didn’t have to think about pain or aggravation at all?

And at the end of the day, most of us just want to be able to play kendama for as long as possible, and as comfortably as possible. I believe that working on yourself physically will ensure this chance to the highest degree.

Take a look at my past couple of videos and let me know what you think

You may find out quickly that this type of work is less about training for kendama and more for a higher quality of life itself. 

DM me if you have any questions, need help getting started, or just want to discuss this🙌🏼

Inspired by @consciouscarnivore1.0 , I attempted 10D5 pull-ups - something that was completely out of my reach just a couple months ago and wasn’t even a certainty at the point of recording this video.

5 pull-ups every minute on the minute for 10 minutes

If I didn’t see the video from Jordan on this day, who knows when I would have attempted this despite being capable of it. It could’ve been weeks or months without trying this. 

Why am I sharing this video? Sure, the physical feat is cool (for me anyway), but the bigger thing I want to express here is the power of influence by those around you…not only physically, but digitally as well.

The internet is a massive tool in today’s age, and I would even go as far to say that some of you reading this are probably being influenced more by digital things you see online than friends, family, or experiences that you have in person. 

My point is this: prioritizing your physical circle AND digital circle is key to the person you become. For in-person that of course means the people you see the most often or make an effort to see, and online that means your group chats, who you’re following, your feed, who you’re texting, your notifications, etc all multiplied by how many apps you have.

Most people reading this are in the kendama community. This is amazing because we already have each other, we’re already being influenced each day to play kendama, become better players, and make friends with each other based on our common interest.

If you’ve felt the impact of positive impact community, in-person or online in your life, then you know what I’m talking about. It’s happened to all of us, your actions have always been influenced by those around you or from what you see online. 

If you have other interests than kendama, are you in a community for that as well? If not, try it out. Communities can unlock your potential. You don’t know how much you could grow just by being around others who have similar interests and goals as yourself!

Everyone has the capability to learn a new skill

But to do that, a person has to try something new.

Most people don’t. 

Unfortunately most of us are conditioned to think that most things “aren’t for us.”

Gaining skill in something, at the very least, instills self-belief via proving to yourself that you can improve provided you put time in. 

At most, it can positively affect your entire life

I reluctantly picked up a Japanese wooden-skill toy at age 11 and my entire life changed. Continuing with kendama for the next 12 years has brought me:

- Connection with tens of thousands of people
- Immense joy
- World-Wide travel
- Incredible friendships
- Mindset and perception expansion
- Deep appreciation and interest for the passions of others

It almost single-handedly guided me into being the person I was from my first year of middle school to a year out of graduating college.

Oh yeah, and all of those would’ve happened if I had been just half as good at it as I am now. 

Point is, starting something new has the potential to not only affect who you are as a person, your perspectives…but your life experiences as well.

Kendama is just one example, pick something new to try that even slightly piques your interest. 

You may very well find a new joy brought into your life that may stem into something more than you ever could have imagined

Kendama changed my life. 
It has played a part in just about every substantial experience I’ve had since I was 12 years old. 

I’ve gone to 7 countries, met thousands of people, competed at the highest level, and have been blessed with life-altering experiences that I never would have gotten without kendama.

How did it have this amazing affect?

I simply began to share my interest in kendama online with others.

Once I started to do this, I began to make more connections with others who also shared my interest.

Not just kendama players either…

Outside of the relationships I built with kendama players, I made insanely fast connections with complete strangers through sharing kendama with them. 

Eventually, opportunities and experiences started to seemingly just appear into my life as if they were completely natural.

And the more I shared my passion, the more I connected with others, the more opportunities that popped into my life.

I can’t help but wonder…what if I just played in silence? 

What if I never took the chance to post about my interest?

What if I never connected with others who shared my interest?

My life wouldn’t be the same. I would have a marginal amount of joy in comparison to what I’ve gotten with kendama, and I wouldn’t have nearly any of the relationships / experiences.

Interests give you a key to connect with others, but it’s up to you to turn the lock.

Talk about your interests with others in-person

Share them online. Social media is a connection TOOL that has the potential to connect even the most isolated of people with thousands of others.

Replace “kendama” in this caption with any other hobby in the world I guarantee millions of others have had very similar experiences. 

Never in my life did I think when I reluctantly tried a wooden cup-and-ball skill toy for the first time when I was 11 that my life would play out as it has.

Point is, you have no idea what could happen if you connect with others about your passion.

Share it and find out

If I had to choose 7 foods for the rest of my life, it would be

Beef🥩

Eggs🥚

Raw Milk🥛

Raw Honey🍯

Butter🧈

Salt🧂

Fruit🥭🍍🫐

I primarily eat these foods. Switching to this modality of eating has had a profound impact on my life and my perspective towards food.

Sound crazy? I would’ve thought so too just 3 months ago. 

I finished 31 days strict carnivore

Reintroduced fruit 

Now I’m feeling the best I’ve ever felt:

🔷High energy levels stabilized throughout day

🔷Absolutely amazing digestion

🔷High performance in workouts 

🔷No cravings

Increased mental clarity - no more feeling slow after a big lunch or dinner

More productive (now eating twice a day instead of 3+)

I want to share this with you guys because I used to think that I had to eat X amount of greens, X amount of carbs, X amount of whichever foods to get all nutrients in order to be “balanced” and feel the best I possibly could.

My thoughts were based on norms, not experience. I had never tried to do anything different. 

Some of the men I respect the most were being vocal about their success on similar modalities of eating. I thought to myself - why not? Why not go for it and see for myself?

That decision has now led to me enjoying myself so much that right now I honestly can’t see myself basing what I eat around any other mixture of foods for years upon years to come.

I’m not guaranteeing this will work for you,

I’m not even asking you to trust me,

But I AM encouraging you a little bit of research on this topic (carnivore style of eating/meat & fruit eating) to hear people’s stories, and to try it out for yourself.

I’ll be going detailing my story fully in the future but you will be amazed on the seemingly magical effects that this modality of eating has brought people….and could bring to you as well.

If anything from this caption has resonated with you, then send me DM and let’s talk.

40lbs in 4 Years - Part 2: Food

If I knew what I knew now, life would’ve been so much easier while trying to put on some weight/size.

I used to

🔴 Eat foods that my body hated

🔴 Overthink EVERYTHING about food intake

🔴 Have no idea what nutrients/ingredients were in the foods I was eating

1. Intend to eat SMARTER, not MORE
 
  Eat foods your body can tolerate. Stomach aches, excess farting, horrible shits, and just awful digestion in general is not the end all be all. I have found that finding foods that I enjoy and that my body tolerates super well makes the process of eating MUCH more enjoyable - resulting in making the process of eating more food very seamless and less chore-like
 
2. Listen to your body
 
  To eat more, to not to eat more, am I doing enough, am I going overboad….all questions that can be answered by simply paying attention to what your body is telling you.
 
  This won’t happen overnight. But when the intent is there, you’re going to start learning. Listen to your hunger signals. Doing this in combination with the foods I mentioned will save you a lot of discomfort and confusion.
 
3. Track Protein
 
  Just becoming aware of how much protein is in foods and how much you’re actually eating is game-changing. Getting enough protein is really important for this journey…and tracking takes the guessing out of it. Track for 2-4 weeks every single day…you’ll quickly pick up a sense of how much protein is in what. 
 
  Not to mention if you’re looking at nutrition labels, then you’re going to becoming more aware of everything else in a food too - ingredients and all. Which is huge for your overall food awareness. 
 
  One last thing I’ll say is that when I say “processed foods,” I mean “ultra-processed foods.” 
 
  Hope this helps. I know I’m not the only guy out there who has struggled with this before.
 
  Why not train? Why not build muscle? I believe we owe it to ourselves to become the best physical version of ourselves that we can be…and I believe these tips will aid everyone in their journeys with that.

I had Osteochondritus Dissecans (OCD) in my left knee for years. It got to the point where that knee felt so fragile that when I was stepping off a curb onto the street, I was consciously making sure I was stepping off with my left instead of my right. Anything to not have my left leg hold up all of my body weight for even a second. I remember another time 

(It was the top range that was particularly bad…so doing that weighted step-up in the video with ease is insane for me to see myself do)

I had 2 surgeries, both extremely successful…

But something still didn’t feel right. I still didn’t feel 100% confident in my left knee EVEN after relearning how to walk/run/sprint…

I continued to take myself out of playing sports/being active with my friends because of my knee an entire 1.5 YEARS after my last surgery.

Basically, my mental state about my knee hardly had changed between pre-surgery and post. 
And why wouldn’t it? I wasn’t doing anything to shrink any chance of going on crutches to the lowest degree AT ALL.

I sympathize with those who have gone through surgery and feel this way…that everything will never be the same with your joint that was operated on again. That you just have a “bad x” and that’s the end of it.

It doesn’t have to be that way.

I took responsibility into my own hands after seeing @kneesovertoesguy & @athletictruthgroup and started the ATG Zero program.

I haven't looked back. Everything ATG has made me aware of has propelled me to be able to all that you see in this video and more. My previous self wouldn't have ever been able to perceive anything like this as a possibility.
